HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1518
By Martin G
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Barry Clingan upon his
recognition by the East Tennessee Historical
Association as a member of the First Families of
Tennessee.
WHEREAS, the East Tennessee Historical Association has recognized Barry Clingan as
a member of the First Families of Tennessee, an honor reserved for those who can document a
direct ancestor present in the region that became Tennessee prior to its admission to the Union
in 1796; and
WHEREAS, Barry Clingan traces his proud Scots-Irish heritage to three Clingan brothers
who immigrated from Donegal, Ireland, in 1739 with their Presbyterian pastor and settled in
Donegal, Pennsylvania; and
WHEREAS, one of these brothers was the father of William Clingan, who served as a
delegate from Pennsylvania to the Second Continental Congress from 1777 to 1779 and signed
the Articles of Confederation on behalf of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, contributing to
the foundational governance of the emerging United States; and
WHEREAS, another branch of the family connects directly to Tennessee through Barry
Clingan's great-great-great-grandfather, Edward Clingan, who was present in the area that
would become Washington County as early as 1790; and
WHEREAS, Edward Clingan's son and Barry Clingan's great-great-grandfather,
Alexander Adams Clingan, received an eighty-acre land grant from Tennessee Governor James
C. Jones in March 1842 in Bradley County on land still known today as Clingan Ridge, where he
is buried in the Clingan Family Cemetery; and
WHEREAS, a Tennessee historical marker at his gravesite recognizes Alexander
Adams Clingan as the first sheriff of Bradley County; and
HJR1518
018215
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Alexander Adams Clingan's wife, Martha Blythe Clingan, was the daughter
of the founders of the historic Blythe Ferry on the Tennessee River, further rooting the family in
early East Tennessee commerce and settlement; and
WHEREAS, Barry Clingan's great-grandfather, Elijah Edward Clingan, continued this
legacy of public service by serving as the first sheriff of James County (now part of Hamilton
County); and
WHEREAS, Barry Clingan was born in Hamilton County and has faithfully served as a
pastor for more than forty years in churches across Tennessee, Georgia, Mississippi, and
Texas, providing spiritual leadership and community guidance; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Clingan and his wife, Amy Thornburg Clingan, are the proud parents of
four adult children, and he remains deeply thankful for his rich Scots-Irish East Tennessee
lineage that embodies the pioneering spirit, faith, and resilience of early Tennesseans; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Barry Clingan upon his recognition by the East
Tennessee Historical Association as a member of the First Families of Tennessee and for the
distinguished heritage and lifelong service he represents.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
